"# Appendix E — Glossary

Short definitions of the words this book leans on. If a word is in a chapter and not in your head, look here.

**cell** — one square on the surface. Each cell has an `x` and a `y`, and can hold one color at a time.

**surface** — the whole grid of cells that the program paints on. In this book, the surface is 40 wide and 30 tall. That is a choice; other surfaces are other sizes.

**frame** — one repaint of the surface. The book assumes 60 frames per second. `(frame)` returns the current frame number, starting at 0.

**paint-cell** — the verb that colors one cell. Takes `x`, `y`, `color`. The most-used verb in the book.

**vector** — two numbers held together, usually `(x y)`. Position, velocity, and force are all vectors.

**force** — a vector that changes velocity. Introduced in ch05.

**oscillation** — motion that comes back. Sine and cosine are the honest way to describe it. Introduced ch06.

**particle** — one small thing with its own position and velocity. A particle field is many of them. Introduced ch07.

**body** — a particle with mass and shape. Introduced ch08.

**locomotion** — motion generated by the moving thing itself, not applied from outside. Legs, wings, wheels. Introduced ch09.

**steering** — locomotion aimed at a target. Introduced ch10.

**flocking** — many steerers who care about each other. Introduced ch11.

**wayfinding** — picking a goal for a steerer, especially when the shortest path is not the straight line. Introduced ch12.

**scene** — a named collection of things, drawn together. Introduced ch13.

**camera** — the piece that decides which part of the scene shows up on the surface. Introduced ch14.

**director** — the piece that decides what should happen next. Introduced ch15.

**living garden** — the book's closing metaphor. A scene where things happen without you having to type each of them. ch16.

Words this book does NOT define but leans on: `let`, `lambda`, `cons`, `car`, `cdr`, `map`, `filter`, `if`, `when`, `define`. Those live in the Book of Scheme."
